“Following a comprehensive review of the economics, logistics and deadlines to meet our ambitious decarbonization targets, we have made the decision to reassess the future of our U.S. manufacturing strategy and no longer proceed with our planned Michigan Manufacturing Center,” a company spokesperson said in a statement to Crain’s on Friday.

Fortescue Zero — the Australian mining company’s green energy investment arm — rolled out plans for the factory in the city’s Milwaukee Junction district in January 2024 as part of its diversification into clean energy. It had planned to redevelop an old industrial building at 601 Piquette Ave., next to the Ford Piquette Avenue Plant Museum.

Construction crews have been performing cleanup and remediation work at the 14-acre site, including electrical upgrades inside the 410,000-square-foot, six-story building. The company is now preparing to put the property on the market and seeking buyers.

Fortescue was awarded $12.7 million in state incentives for the project last year, as well as $11 million worth of Detroit brownfield incentives. The company has not received any of the funds or incentives, the Michigan Economic Development Corp. confirmed to Crain's. Fortescue is working to close out its contracts with the city and state.

“While we are grateful for the strong support received from the Governor, Mayor and Detroit community, we must do everything we can to remain focused on opportunities to meet our near-term global decarbonization goals,” the company said in the statement.

Production had been anticipated to start in the fourth quarter. Fortescue’s plan was to first build packs for watercraft powertrain systems with cells sourced from Asia, before moving into the high-performance segment of passenger vehicles.

EV battery investment has gone from boom to bust. Michigan spent hundreds of millions of taxpayer dollars to lure EV projects that may no longer have a business case as the Trump administration slashes EV tax credits and rolls back gas emissions rules, and consumer demand for EVs cools.

Ford Motor Co.’s EV battery plant in Marshall, which was scaled down significantly in size and jobs promised, is among the few survivors in the wave of advanced manufacturing investment promises Michigan landed during EV fever a few years ago. For example:

General Motors Co. switched its Orion Assembly plant from EVs to gas-powered pickups and SUVs and pulled out of an LG Energy joint venture battery plant near Lansing;

Our Next Energy is treading water without a clear path to deliver the $1.6 billion battery factory and 2,100 jobs in Van Buren Township promised in 2022;

Gotion’s $2.6 billion battery plant near Big Rapids is on indefinite hold;

CustomCells’ plan for a $100 million plant and 250 jobs in Warren is dead;

the $400 million Nel Hydrogen factory in Plymouth Township was mothballed;

BorgWarner shut down its EV battery operation in Michigan and laid off 188;

Plastic Omnium walked away from a $171 million hydrogen project in Grand Blanc; and

GM is mulling whether to pull the plug on its hydrogen plant in Detroit.

The latest — and largest — scrapped project in Michigan was Sandisk's $63 billion semiconductor complex and 10,000 jobs near Flint. The company, which Michigan had been courting for years, abandoned the project due to "massive economic uncertainty at the national level," Gov. Gretchen Whitmer said.

For its part, Fortescue said it will “continue to explore opportunities to advance zero emission technologies” in the U.S. even as it pulls the plug in Detroit.

“Current policy settings and market conditions in the United States, including recent changes to critical tax credits, have created significant uncertainty around the viability of long-term investment in advanced manufacturing,” the company said.

A 2026 Chevrolet Silverado EV range milestone has been set, with the Max Range Work Truck traveling 1,059.2 miles on a full charge during a GM engineering test. This achievement surpasses the previous world record of 749 miles, set earlier this year by Lucid.

The idea started as a casual conversation among GM engineers in late 2024, evolving into a challenge to see how far the Silverado EV could go under optimal conditions. Initial estimates ranged from 800 to 1,000 miles.

“Getting this kind of range on a full charge doesn’t happen by accident,” said Kurt Kelty, VP, battery, propulsion, and sustainability. “It takes deep integration across battery chemistry, drive unit efficiency, software and vehicle engineering. That’s exactly what the team delivered. This achievement is a great example of how far our EV technology has come. It’s the kind of innovation we’re building on every day at GM.”

Real-World Chevrolet Silverado EV Range Test

The engineers drove a production Silverado EV Max Range WT on public roads near GM’s Milford Proving Ground, finishing on Detroit’s Belle Isle. The truck’s hardware and software remained unchanged, but Chevy said drivers optimized habits and settings, all within the owner’s manual.

Adjustments included:

Maintaining a steady 20–25 mph when safe;

Reducing hard braking and acceleration;

Optimizing wheel alignment;

Removing the spare tire to reduce weight;

Using a tonneau cover for smoother airflow;

Inflating tires to maximum recommended pressure;

Turning off climate control for efficiency.

The test was conducted in summer conditions, ideal for battery performance.

The team found the Silverado EV’s most efficient cruising speed was 20–25 mph.

Record-Breaking Achievement

With its EPA-estimated 493-mile range, GM’s research confirms that range is a key buying factor for Silverado EV customers.

The engineering team’s efforts not only set a world record but also exceeded their own 1,000-mile goal. To commemorate the achievement, they recharged the Silverado EV after the test to power a 3D printer that created a trophy celebrating the accomplishment.
